│ The `createNewAccess` function is responsible for determining whether an instruction       │
│ interacts with memory and creating the appropriate `MemoryUseOrDef` object. The issue      │
│ arises when the function concludes that an instruction does not interact with memory       │
│ (`!Def && !Use`), returning `nullptr`. This behavior is problematic for `call`             │
│ instructions, which may have side effects even if they do not explicitly read from or      │
│ write to memory.                                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ To address this, we need to modify the function to handle `call` instructions more         │
│ conservatively. Specifically, we should treat `call` instructions as potentially           │
│ interacting with memory unless proven otherwise. This can be achieved by adding a special  │
│ case for `call` instructions before the `ModRefInfo` check.                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now edit the function to implement this fix.                                        │
